-- 
Asian Stocks Drop as Materials Prices Fall, Earnings Disappoint

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s   a n d   N i c h o l a   S a m i n a t h e r
-- 
2011-05-04T10:43:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-04/asian-stocks-decline-as-raw-material-producers-australian-banks-retreat.html
Asian stocks declined, with a regional
benchmark index heading for a two-week low, as raw material
producers fell and companies from  Westpac Banking Corp. (WBC)  to
 Chimei Innolux Corp. (3481)  posted earnings that missed analysts’
estimates.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) , the world’s biggest mining company and
Australia’s largest oil and gas producer, slipped 0.8 percent in
Sydney as oil and copper futures declined. Westpac Banking Corp.,
Australia’s No. 2 lender, lost 2.5 percent. Chimei Innolux Corp.,
a Taiwanese maker of liquid-crystal displays, sank 2.4 percent.
 Citic Resources Holdings Ltd. (1205)  plunged 9.7 percent after
announcing a HK$2.5 billion ($322 million) share sale.  “Confession season is well under way with expectations
that further downward momentum in earnings guidance can be
expected as companies continue to find the headwinds,” said  Tim Schroeders , Melbourne-based manager at Pengana Capital Ltd.,
which oversees about A$1 billion. “There was little in the way
of positive news overnight for commodity-related sectors.”  The MSCI Asia Pacific Excluding Japan Index dropped 1.2
percent to 496.34 as of 6:22 p.m. in  Hong Kong , set for its
lowest close since April 19. Almost two stocks fell for each
that advanced.  The measure lost 0.3 percent last week as companies from
Acer Inc. to LG Electronics Inc. posted earnings that missed
estimates, sparking concern global growth may not be sustained
even as the U.S. Federal Reserve renewed its pledge to stimulate
the world’s biggest economy by keeping  interest rates  low.  China  Inflation  China’s Shanghai Composite Index declined 2.3 percent after
the nation’s central bank said taming inflation is its top
priority, signaling that more tightening is possible even after
a manufacturing survey showed growth may be moderating in Asia’s
biggest economy. Hong Kong’s Hang Seng Index dropped 1.4 percent.  South Korea’s Kospi Index sank 0.9 percent and Singapore’s
Straits Times Index declined 1.3 percent. Australia’s S&P/ASX
200 Index dropped 0.9 percent, while New Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index (NZSE50FG) 
was little changed. Japanese markets are closed for a public
holiday.  Futures on the U.S. Standard & Poor’s 500 Index were little
changed today. U.S. stocks dropped in  New York  yesterday for a
second day as commodity shares slid and  Sears Holdings Corp. (SHLD)  led
retailers lower after reporting a first-quarter loss. The  S&P
500  lost 0.3 percent to 1,356.62 in New York. The  Dow Jones
Industrial Average  was unchanged at 12,807.51.  Oil, Copper  Financial and industrial companies as well as raw material
producers registered the biggest declines among the 10 industry
groups in the MSCI Asia Pacific Excluding Japan Index, all of
which declined.  BHP Billiton dropped 0.8 percent to A$45.15 in Sydney.
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd. (WPL) , Australia’s second-biggest oil and gas
producer, declined 2.5 percent to A$44.70. Jiangxi Copper Co.,
China’s No. 1 producer of the metal, sank 1.9 percent to
HK$25.35.  Cnooc Ltd. (883) , China’s largest offshore oil producer,
fell 2.6 percent to HK$18.78 in Hong Kong.  Oil for June delivery decreased as much as 0.7 percent to
$110.23 a barrel in electronic trading on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange , extending its decline for a third day, as
U.S. crude stockpiles increased, sparking concern demand for
fuel will fall. Three-month copper dropped as much as 1.8
percent to $9,178 a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange, the
lowest price since March 16.  Rio Tinto Group, the world’s second-biggest mining company
by sales, dropped 1.5 percent to A$80.88 in Sydney. Alcoa Ltd.
saw record bullish options trading in New York on speculation
Rio Tinto may make a takeover offer for the largest U.S.
aluminum producer.  Westpac, Chimei  Westpac Banking declined 2.5 percent to A$24.11. The lender
said first-half cash profit rose 7 percent from a year earlier
to A$3.17 billion ($3.43 billion) as bad debts fell and home
lending increased. Net profit, which includes a A$1.1 billion
reduction in tax related to its 2008 St. George Bank purchase,
rose 38 percent to A$3.96 billion, missing the A$4.13 billion
median estimate of four analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News.  Chimei Innolux, Taiwan’s largest LCD maker, fell 2.4
percent to NT$28.30 in Taipei. The company posted a first-
quarter net loss of NT$13.8 billion ($483 million) as prices
failed to rebound and production problems delayed output of
advanced panels. The average estimate of nine analysts compiled
by Bloomberg was for a net loss of NT$9.7 billion.  The MSCI  Asia  Pacific Excluding Japan Index climbed 4.9
percent this year through yesterday, compared with gains of 7.9
percent by the S&P 500 and 2.4 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600
Index. Stocks in the Asian benchmark index are valued at 12.9
times estimated earnings on average as of the last close,
compared with 13.7 times for the S&P 500 and 11.4 times for the
Stoxx 600.  Asian Earnings  About 42 percent of companies on the Asian benchmark index
that reported earnings since April 11 beat analysts’ estimates.
That compares with 62 percent for the MSCI World Index of
developed stock markets.  Citic Resources tumbled 9.7 percent to HK$1.68, the worst
performer on the Hang Seng Composite Index. The company said it
will raise HK$2.5 billion by selling 1.82 billion shares at
HK$1.38 each to existing shareholders.  Tencent Holdings Ltd. (700) , China’s biggest internet company by
revenue, declined 3.3 percent to HK$211.60 in Hong Kong. China
has set up a new department to supervise the Internet, as the
government steps up efforts to tighten control over the world’s
largest online market.  To contact the reporters for this story:
